  "text": "In view of the essentiality of cerebral ultrasound findings in predicting neonatal outcome, the development of fetal MRI has become an asset in the assessment of infected fetuses. In a study by Picone et al., 46% of cases with only extracerebral abnormalities on ultrasound were found to have cerebral abnormalities on MRI. In cases with cerebral features seen on ultrasound, MRI maybe used to confirm these and to detect further abnormalities [CITATION_1] . In our case described, in view of the severity of the obvious cerebral features on ultrasound, the multiorgan involvement as well as fetal thrombocytopenia, the prognosis was determined to be poor and the need for fetal MRI was deferred.",
